Persistent AF/Flutter LAAO
The anatomic and physiologic basis of atrial fibrillation, as well as the risk for left atrial thrombus formation and embolic stroke was discussed in detail. In view of the CHADSVASC2 score, he is at high risk for stroke and therefore needs a strategy for stroke prophylaxis. Thus, there are two general issues that we discussed with him: 1) rhythm management, and 2) stroke prophylaxis.
With regard to rhythm management, we discussed at length the various therapeutic options available including trials of antiarrhythmic drug therapy, radiofrequency catheter ablation, and the surgical Maze procedure. The advantages, limitations, and risks of these approaches were reviewed in detail. We believe that the approach most likely to succeed in rhythm control is radiofrequency catheter ablation. In addition to the procedural details of AF catheter ablation, we also discussed that while unlikely, catheter ablation is associated with several potential complications including, but not limited to, vascular complications, atrio-esophageal fistula, pulmonary vein stenosis, stroke, pericardial effusion/tamponade, phrenic nerve injury, and death. We also explained that with the history of persistent atrial fibrillation, the AF ablation procedure (to achieve sinus rhythm) would require ablation beyond simply isolating the pulmonary veins. That is, for persistent atrial fibrillation, we typically must also place additional ablation lesions (ablation of sites of complex atrial activity and, sometimes, linear lesions) in both the right and left atria. Because of the extent of ablation, the incidence of atypical left atrial flutters (or Atrial Tachycardias) is high after the procedure. And in fact, we explained that we should simply plan for the need to do two procedures to achieve sinus rhythm (unlike for paroxysmal atrial fibrillation patients who typically require one procedure): the first procedure to organize the atrial fibrillation and the second to eliminate the atypical flutters.
With regard to stroke prophylaxis, we discussed various options including long-term anticoagulation, and the possibility of left atrial appendage closure using the Watchman device. Clinical trials have demonstrated that the left atrial appendage (LAA) is the major source of the thrombi causing embolic stroke in most patients with atrial fibrillation. Accordingly, the Watchman device is placed at the opening of the left atrial appendage to prevent any potential thrombi from embolizing. Eventually the LAA will be completely occluded. The advantages, limitations, and risks of the Watchman device relative to Coumadin therapy have been reviewed in detail. We explained that the Watchman device has been approved by the FDA and is an excellent alternative to long term Coumadin. In addition to the procedural details Watchman implantation, we also discussed that there are several potential complications including, but not limited to, vascular complications, pericardial effusion/tamponade, stroke, and device dislodgment requiring surgery; however, I explained that in experienced hands, theses complications are extremely rare.
We also discussed the option of ligation of the LAA with a suture. This can be done in a non-surgical fashion by using a sub-xyphoid pericardial puncture approach that we are quite familiar with. We discussed that this also has the potential for complications including pericardial effusion, emergent cardiac surgery, cardiac tamponade and stroke.
He appeared to understand the whole discussion and verbalized that all of his questions were answered to satisfaction. After deliberating over the options, explanation, and risks/ benefits of left atrial appendage occlusion with watchman, he agreed to proceed with the procedure.
I will refer him to IVR for consideration of retrieval of the IVC filter in preparation for left atrial appendage occlusion.
I will order a CT of the left atrium and left atrial appendage to rule out intracardiac thrombi and assess the anatomy and dimensions of the appendage.
I will see him again in 2 weeks.

item.paragraph:
Wright Kelly MD: PERFORM
Event Display: Cardiology Office Clinic Note
Authored Date: 20230922104733-0500

Chief Complaint
A. fib/flutter with course complicated by GI bleed, subdural hematoma and epistaxis for possible left atrial appendage occlusion
Assessment/Plan
1. Atrial flutter (I48.92: Unspecified atrial flutter)
2. Chronic kidney disease, stage 3b, GFR 33, Creatinine 1.84 Labs 2023-02-28 (N18.32: Chronic kidney disease, stage 3b)
3. Anemia (D64.9: Anemia, unspecified)
4. Presence of IVC filter (Z95.828: Presence of other vascular implants and grafts)
5. Atrial fibrillation (I48.91: Unspecified atrial fibrillation)
6. Subdural hematoma (S06.5X9A: Traumatic subdural hemorrhage with loss of consciousness of unspecified duration, initial encounter)
Persistent AF/Flutter LAAO
The anatomic and physiologic basis of atrial fibrillation, as well as the risk for left atrial thrombus formation and embolic stroke was discussed in detail. In view of the CHADSVASC2 score, he is at high risk for stroke and therefore needs a strategy for stroke prophylaxis. Thus, there are two general issues that we discussed with him: 1) rhythm management, and 2) stroke prophylaxis.
With regard to rhythm management, we discussed at length the various therapeutic options available including trials of antiarrhythmic drug therapy, radiofrequency catheter ablation, and the surgical Maze procedure. The advantages, limitations, and risks of these approaches were reviewed in detail. We believe that the approach most likely to succeed in rhythm control is radiofrequency catheter ablation. In addition to the procedural details of AF catheter ablation, we also discussed that while unlikely, catheter ablation is associated with several potential complications including, but not limited to, vascular complications, atrio-esophageal fistula, pulmonary vein stenosis, stroke, pericardial effusion/tamponade, phrenic nerve injury, and death. We also explained that with the history of persistent atrial fibrillation, the AF ablation procedure (to achieve sinus rhythm) would require ablation beyond simply isolating the pulmonary veins. That is, for persistent atrial fibrillation, we typically must also place additional ablation lesions (ablation of sites of complex atrial activity and, sometimes, linear lesions) in both the right and left atria. Because of the extent of ablation, the incidence of atypical left atrial flutters (or Atrial Tachycardias) is high after the procedure. And in fact, we explained that we should simply plan for the need to do two procedures to achieve sinus rhythm (unlike for paroxysmal atrial fibrillation patients who typically require one procedure): the first procedure to organize the atrial fibrillation and the second to eliminate the atypical flutters.
With regard to stroke prophylaxis, we discussed various options including long-term anticoagulation, and the possibility of left atrial appendage closure using the Watchman device. Clinical trials have demonstrated that the left atrial appendage (LAA) is the major source of the thrombi causing embolic stroke in most patients with atrial fibrillation. Accordingly, the Watchman device is placed at the opening of the left atrial appendage to prevent any potential thrombi from embolizing. Eventually the LAA will be completely occluded. The advantages, limitations, and risks of the Watchman device relative to Coumadin therapy have been reviewed in detail. We explained that the Watchman device has been approved by the FDA and is an excellent alternative to long term Coumadin. In addition to the procedural details Watchman implantation, we also discussed that there are several potential complications including, but not limited to, vascular complications, pericardial effusion/tamponade, stroke, and device dislodgment requiring surgery; however, I explained that in experienced hands, theses complications are extremely rare.
We also discussed the option of ligation of the LAA with a suture. This can be done in a non-surgical fashion by using a sub-xyphoid pericardial puncture approach that we are quite familiar with. We discussed that this also has the potential for complications including pericardial effusion, emergent cardiac surgery, cardiac tamponade and stroke.
He appeared to understand the whole discussion and verbalized that all of his questions were answered to satisfaction. After deliberating over the options, explanation, and risks/ benefits of left atrial appendage occlusion with watchman, he agreed to proceed with the procedure.
I will refer him to IVR for consideration of retrieval of the IVC filter in preparation for left atrial appendage occlusion.
I will order a CT of the left atrium and left atrial appendage to rule out intracardiac thrombi and assess the anatomy and dimensions of the appendage.
I will see him again in 2 weeks.
